( crowd cheers )

758
00:44:18,554 --> 00:44:20,249
And that is surely the goal

759
00:44:20,356 --> 00:44:22,654
which takes Kilnockie through
to the semis.

760
00:44:22,759 --> 00:44:24,784
It's also the goal
of the competition.

761
00:44:24,894 --> 00:44:26,953
If he was Brazilian,
we would be talking about

762
00:44:27,063 --> 00:44:28,894
this goal for the rest
of the season.

763
00:44:28,998 --> 00:44:31,523
There's talkers
and there's fucking doers.

764
00:44:31,634 --> 00:44:33,602
Just like I'm doing
your fucking missus.

765
00:44:33,703 --> 00:44:35,898
- You shouldn't let her go.
- What did you say?

766
00:44:36,005 --> 00:44:38,030
That's a sweet fucking shag,
your wife Jackie.

767
00:44:38,141 --> 00:44:39,904
But wait a minute,
what's happening here?

768
00:44:40,009 --> 00:44:42,239
He's lost the plot!

769
00:44:42,345 --> 00:44:45,246
He's lashed out,
it's McQuillan at McCall.

770
00:44:45,348 --> 00:44:47,441
- Words were said.
- See you later, asshole.

771
00:44:47,550 --> 00:44:51,543
McQuillan lashed out
and there's only one outcome.

772
00:44:51,654 --> 00:44:53,849
Referee Willie Young
holds up the red card.

773
00:44:53,956 --> 00:44:56,186
McQuillan off.
Kilnockie down to 10 men.

774
00:44:56,292 --> 00:44:58,192
- I give up.
- What is he doing?

775
00:44:58,294 --> 00:45:01,695
He's absolutely mad.

776
00:45:01,798 --> 00:45:05,529
In those 15 seconds,
we've just seen a cameo of this man.

777
00:45:05,635 --> 00:45:07,535
From the sheer brilliance
of a hat trick,

778
00:45:07,637 --> 00:45:09,696
to the sheer stupidity
of his actions.

779
00:45:09,806 --> 00:45:12,400
- Unbelievable.
- Fuck's sake !

780
00:45:12,508 --> 00:45:14,499
Get your fucking sellin' out
on the road.

781
00:45:14,610 --> 00:45:16,874
What are you fucking
on about?!

782
00:45:16,979 --> 00:45:19,038
He might need that
medical bag if the manager,

783
00:45:19,148 --> 00:45:20,877
Gordon McCleod, gets to him.

784
00:45:24,987 --> 00:45:27,148
Reporter:
What prompted the fight, Gordon?

785
00:45:27,256 --> 00:45:30,714
You know Jackie, he could start
a fight in an empty house.

786
00:45:30,827 --> 00:45:32,385
What did you tell him?

787
00:45:32,495 --> 00:45:35,396
I told him you cannot score
from the stands.

788
00:45:35,498 --> 00:45:38,399
A wee bit of the old Jackie
out there today, aye, Gordon?

789
00:45:38,501 --> 00:45:39,627
Aye, aye.

790
00:45:39,735 --> 00:45:42,727
But old or new, eh,
old or new,

791
00:45:42,839 --> 00:45:45,399
it's the team that win
or loses.

792
00:45:45,508 --> 00:45:47,567
I like the way
my lads hung on at the end.

793
00:45:47,677 --> 00:45:50,510
There have been some rumors
about your team going to Dublin.

794
00:45:50,613 --> 00:45:52,843
Can you comment on that?

795
00:45:52,949 --> 00:45:54,849
I think the Irish
have enough troubles

796
00:45:54,951 --> 00:45:57,647
without sending them
this team.

797
00:45:57,753 --> 00:46:00,347
- Thanks, Jackie.
- No problem.

798
00:46:05,962 --> 00:46:08,692
Maybe someday my own kid
will get to see me play, eh?

799
00:46:08,798 --> 00:46:10,197
Oh, play.

800
00:46:10,299 --> 00:46:12,824
Is that what you call
your performance today?

801
00:46:12,935 --> 00:46:14,960
Why do you think
I stopped bringing him?

802
00:46:15,071 --> 00:46:17,539
- That guy was a wanker.
- And you had absolutely

803
00:46:17,640 --> 00:46:20,632
no trouble sinking
to his level, did you?

804
00:46:20,743 --> 00:46:22,540
Dad's dream is winning
that Cup.

805
00:46:22,645 --> 00:46:24,203
Now you're defending him.

806
00:46:24,313 --> 00:46:26,838
It'd be a bad living defending
the likes of you two.

807
00:46:26,949 --> 00:46:29,543
I'm driving.

808
00:46:29,652 --> 00:46:33,213
How come everybody's driving
my fucking car but me?

809
00:46:58,781 --> 00:47:00,908
Drinking beer out
of a whiskey bottle?

810
00:47:06,289 --> 00:47:07,847
What are we doing here?

811
00:47:07,957 --> 00:47:09,982
How can you know
where you're going, Jackie,

812
00:47:10,092 --> 00:47:12,060
if you can't remember
where you're from?

813
00:47:12,161 --> 00:47:13,719
The Gorbals.

814
00:47:13,829 --> 00:47:16,525
The birthplace of the great
Jackie McQuillan.

815
00:47:17,833 --> 00:47:20,597
You say you want
to get back together.

816
00:47:20,703 --> 00:47:22,694
You can't even pull
yourself together.

817
00:47:22,805 --> 00:47:24,568
You're sill drinking.

818
00:47:24,674 --> 00:47:27,370
Still getting tossed out
of games.

819
00:47:27,476 --> 00:47:29,205
So what's changed, huh?

820
00:47:29,312 --> 00:47:31,212
What is different
since I left?

821
00:47:31,314 --> 00:47:33,373
What's in it for me
and little Jackie,

822
00:47:33,482 --> 00:47:35,507
except more of the same?

823
00:47:39,155 --> 00:47:41,282
Katie, where are you going?

824
00:47:42,658 --> 00:47:44,125
Home.

825
00:47:44,227 --> 00:47:46,718
At least I know where it is.

826
00:47:55,104 --> 00:47:57,004
There's no danger
of her being here, eh?

827
00:47:57,106 --> 00:47:59,506
Honest to God, Gordon,

828
00:47:59,609 --> 00:48:02,169
you'd think it was a virus
you were discussing

829
00:48:02,278 --> 00:48:04,337
and not your own flesh
and blood.

830
00:48:07,049 --> 00:48:08,949
( bell rings )

831
00:48:14,123 --> 00:48:16,023
Granny!
Grandpa !

832
00:48:16,125 --> 00:48:18,355
Oh, my wee man,
how are you doing?

833
00:48:18,461 --> 00:48:20,952
Maggie?
Maggie, it's us.

834
00:49:58,994 --> 00:50:00,894
Striker, eh?

835
00:50:14,343 --> 00:50:16,402
Rangers' quarter-final
victory today

836
00:50:16,512 --> 00:50:19,208
was overshadowed
by violence which broke out

837
00:50:19,315 --> 00:50:22,341
inside Ibrox with little more
than a minute to play

838
00:50:22,451 --> 00:50:24,749
and spilled
onto the streets.

839
00:50:24,854 --> 00:50:26,583
Police were able
to restore order,

840
00:50:26,689 --> 00:50:28,350
but not before
three supporters

841
00:50:28,457 --> 00:50:30,152
were taken
to the hospital.

842
00:50:30,259 --> 00:50:31,590
Another dozen were arrested

843
00:50:31,694 --> 00:50:34,128
- and flare-ups were reported...
- Hurry up, Campbell.

844
00:50:35,698 --> 00:50:39,031
Rangers go through with
a four-two victory at home.

845
00:50:39,135 --> 00:50:42,730
But the score is still being settled
in some parts of Glasgow.

846
00:50:42,838 --> 00:50:44,931
In other Cup
quarter-final action,

847
00:50:45,040 --> 00:50:46,667
Dunfermline
were victors today

848
00:50:46,776 --> 00:50:48,937
along with Kilmarnock
and little Kilnockie.

849
00:50:52,581 --> 00:50:54,208
Come on !

850
00:50:56,585 --> 00:50:58,314
Quick, get in the car!

851
00:50:58,421 --> 00:50:59,581
Move quick.

852
00:50:59,688 --> 00:51:01,315
I'm Jackie McQuillan.
Now move.

853
00:51:01,424 --> 00:51:03,392
Quick.

854
00:51:03,492 --> 00:51:05,892
What are you doing?
Are you stupid?

855
00:51:05,995 --> 00:51:07,895
You should know better
than that.

856
00:51:11,567 --> 00:51:13,728
You're lucky I was the one
that picked you up.

857
00:51:13,836 --> 00:51:16,066
- Make sure he gets home, boss.
- No problem.

858
00:51:16,172 --> 00:51:18,231
Cheers.

859
00:51:18,340 --> 00:51:21,241
By the way, if I had a real top,
I'd give you one.

860
00:51:22,678 --> 00:51:24,407
Okay?

861
00:51:28,851 --> 00:51:31,752
Vendor: Evening Times !

862
00:51:31,854 --> 00:51:34,414
Times !

863
00:51:34,523 --> 00:51:36,582
Evening Times !

864
00:51:41,197 --> 00:51:43,757
Gordon: The problem is,
people don't change.

865
00:51:43,866 --> 00:51:45,993
No, not in the basic way.

866
00:51:46,101 --> 00:51:48,092
No matter what happens,

867
00:51:48,204 --> 00:51:50,695
what they go through,
what they stand to lose.

868
00:51:51,974 --> 00:51:53,874
You are what you are.

869
00:51:55,478 --> 00:51:56,877
Aye.

870
00:52:00,983 --> 00:52:05,215
Just be as hard on yourself
as you are on others.

871
00:52:07,323 --> 00:52:09,018
You too, eh?

872
00:52:09,124 --> 00:52:12,059
- ( laughs )
- Gordon.

873
00:52:16,165 --> 00:52:17,723
That's fine, Irene.

874
00:52:17,833 --> 00:52:19,391
No, no, that's fine.

875
00:52:23,506 --> 00:52:27,237
I'm not saying there haven't
been disappointments.

876
00:52:27,343 --> 00:52:29,072
Disappointments?

877
00:52:29,178 --> 00:52:31,009
What are you talking about?

878
00:52:31,113 --> 00:52:33,877
Jackie getting red-carded
isn't a disappointment,

879
00:52:33,983 --> 00:52:35,746
just an accident waiting
to happen.

880
00:52:35,851 --> 00:52:38,251
I'm surprised it took so long.

881
00:52:38,354 --> 00:52:40,914
What I don't need is you
or anyone else telling me

882
00:52:41,023 --> 00:52:43,583
how I'm supposed to feel
when people knife me

883
00:52:43,692 --> 00:52:45,922
in the back or take something
precious from me.

884
00:52:47,530 --> 00:52:50,431
I just think it's time
you let something precious

885
00:52:50,533 --> 00:52:52,364
back into your life.

886
00:52:52,468 --> 00:52:55,835
It'll be time
when it's time, okay?

887
00:53:01,644 --> 00:53:04,374
But seeing
those pictures today...

888
00:53:04,480 --> 00:53:06,038
of wee Jackie,

889
00:53:09,485 --> 00:53:13,546
it was like viewing something
beautiful while walking on glass.

890
00:53:13,656 --> 00:53:16,386
'Cause here
there was only joy.

891
00:53:16,492 --> 00:53:19,723
But in my guts,
deep down,

892
00:53:19,828 --> 00:53:21,728
it's a terrible gnawing.

893
00:53:23,666 --> 00:53:25,896
'Cause, Irene,
there's not a day that passes

894
00:53:28,671 --> 00:53:30,332
( sobbing )

895
00:53:33,842 --> 00:53:37,243
I don't think about Katie.
My sweet, sweet Katie.

896
00:53:41,016 --> 00:53:42,745
Not a minute I don't hurt.

897
00:53:53,128 --> 00:53:56,859
But it wasn't me who married outside
the church she was brought up in,

898
00:53:56,966 --> 00:54:00,527
just like it wasn't me who hung
his best friend out to dry.

899
00:54:00,636 --> 00:54:02,695
Nor is it me who pissed
away more talent

900
00:54:02,805 --> 00:54:05,535
than God gave any other
10 players put together.

901
00:54:05,641 --> 00:54:09,338
But it was me...

902
00:54:09,445 --> 00:54:12,243
who had his daughter stolen
from him.

903
00:54:12,348 --> 00:54:15,044
- Jackie never stole Kate--
- She was engaged to be married

904
00:54:15,150 --> 00:54:17,710
to another man when Jackie McQuillan
stepped into her life.

905
00:54:17,820 --> 00:54:20,584
- What do you call that?
- They fell in love, Gordon.

906
00:54:20,689 --> 00:54:22,714
You can't change some things.

907
00:54:22,825 --> 00:54:24,554
You just said it.

908
00:54:25,828 --> 00:54:28,729
But you can change the way
you look at things

909
00:54:28,831 --> 00:54:31,299
and think about them.

910
00:54:31,400 --> 00:54:33,891
So tell me,
just how are you looking

911
00:54:34,003 --> 00:54:36,062
at the prospect
of me looking for a job

912
00:54:36,171 --> 00:54:40,073
when the team moves
to Dublin?

913
00:55:09,805 --> 00:55:11,864
You only betray yourself,
Gordon,

914
00:55:11,974 --> 00:55:13,874
if you can't let go

915
00:55:13,976 --> 00:55:15,876
of the things
that cause you pain.

916
00:55:17,146 --> 00:55:20,877
I don't care if you ever talk
to Martin Smith again.

917
00:55:22,484 --> 00:55:24,714
But it's not the same
with Kate.

918
00:55:26,989 --> 00:55:29,890
She loves you
with all her heart.

919
00:55:32,327 --> 00:55:33,658
And you know why?

920
00:55:34,997 --> 00:55:38,899
Because some things
never change.

921
00:56:17,806 --> 00:56:19,535
( crowd cheering )

922
00:57:19,234 --> 00:57:21,134
( yelling )

923
00:57:28,911 --> 00:57:30,811
Yes !

924
00:57:30,913 --> 00:57:32,813
Promoted
to the First Division, man.

925
00:57:34,149 --> 00:57:35,707
Congratulations.

926
00:57:37,319 --> 00:57:38,877
Listen to these guys.

927
00:57:38,987 --> 00:57:41,046
Is that good enough
to keep us here?

928
00:57:43,158 --> 00:57:45,752
You're the talk of all Scotland.
Everybody's digging you.

929
00:57:45,861 --> 00:57:47,886
Let's just keep everybody talking
till you and me

930
00:57:47,996 --> 00:57:49,930
are drinking
from the Cup, huh?

931
00:57:52,267 --> 00:57:54,497
- Towels, boys.
- ( yelling )

932
00:57:58,941 --> 00:58:00,841
( laughs )

933
00:58:02,110 --> 00:58:04,169
That's outrageous, eh?

934
00:58:05,447 --> 00:58:07,540
Right. Okay.

935
00:58:07,649 --> 00:58:10,982
Let's see if you can beat
your old man with a spot kick.

936
00:58:11,086 --> 00:58:13,520
Don't fancy.
Give it your best.

937
00:58:13,622 --> 00:58:15,180
Come on.

938
00:58:16,625 --> 00:58:18,320
Yeah !

939
00:58:18,427 --> 00:58:20,190
Yeah !

940
00:58:24,967 --> 00:58:26,366
You know your trouble?

941
00:58:26,468 --> 00:58:28,527
You've been watching too much
Italian football.

942
00:58:28,637 --> 00:58:31,538
- I haven't.
- You have. Now come here.

943
00:58:32,975 --> 00:58:35,944
The whole object
is to be cool.

944
00:58:36,044 --> 00:58:37,875
Scoring a goal should be
as natural

945
00:58:37,980 --> 00:58:40,210
as having your breakfast.

946
00:58:40,315 --> 00:58:43,807
Usually one fist gets
the job done.

947
00:58:43,919 --> 00:58:46,547
The attitude should be

948
00:58:46,655 --> 00:58:48,714
plenty more
where that came from.

949
00:58:49,958 --> 00:58:52,688
Now, let's talk about
the goal.

950
00:58:52,794 --> 00:58:54,989
The spectacular goal.

951
00:58:55,097 --> 00:58:56,826
The goal that wins
the Cup Final.

952
00:58:58,133 --> 00:59:00,761
What you've got to do is freeze
and capture the moment.

953
00:59:00,869 --> 00:59:04,600
Both hands in the air,
fists raised.

954
00:59:04,706 --> 00:59:07,300
You don't move,
and you remember...

955
00:59:07,409 --> 00:59:11,846
all these people in the stadium
are here because of you.

956
00:59:13,949 --> 00:59:15,416
How's this?

957
00:59:15,517 --> 00:59:17,485
Perfect.

958
00:59:17,586 --> 00:59:20,020
Now, here's the set-up.

959
00:59:22,124 --> 00:59:24,024
Cup Final.

960
00:59:24,126 --> 00:59:25,684
Hampden Park.

961
00:59:25,794 --> 00:59:28,092
50,000 fans.

962
00:59:28,196 --> 00:59:30,528
It's a penalty shoot out.

963
00:59:30,632 --> 00:59:33,362
Everybody's scored.

964
00:59:33,468 --> 00:59:36,028
And you have got
the last kick.

965
00:59:36,138 --> 00:59:37,696
You know something?

966
00:59:40,142 --> 00:59:41,803
You're shitting your pants.

967
00:59:41,910 --> 00:59:43,605
You've got to beat me.

968
00:59:44,813 --> 00:59:46,644
Right, come on.

969
00:59:46,748 --> 00:59:48,340
Oh ! Now remember...

970
00:59:48,450 --> 00:59:52,216
50,000 fans.

971
00:59:53,655 --> 00:59:55,520
Can you hear them?

972
00:59:55,624 --> 00:59:57,717
Give me your best.
Come on then, give us it.

973
01:00:02,164 --> 01:00:04,325
Yeah !

974
01:00:10,672 --> 01:00:12,572
Are you all right?

975
01:00:12,674 --> 01:00:14,539
I just keep thinking
about that boy.

976
01:00:16,345 --> 01:00:18,870
It could just as easily
have been wee Jackie, you know?

977
01:00:18,981 --> 01:00:21,074
Wearing his Celtic top

978
01:00:21,183 --> 01:00:22,878
in the wrong part of town.

979
01:00:22,985 --> 01:00:25,977
About to get hurt because
of that.

980
01:00:27,356 --> 01:00:29,051
Yeah, well,
you saved him, babe.

981
01:00:29,157 --> 01:00:31,489
You should be
happy about that.

982
01:00:31,593 --> 01:00:34,426
You know the press, they blew
everything out of proportion.

983
01:00:35,697 --> 01:00:37,562
Those kids never even
saw him.

984
01:00:41,703 --> 01:00:44,228
It's still us versus them.

985
01:00:44,339 --> 01:00:46,330
I mean, look at your father.

986
01:00:46,441 --> 01:00:50,207
He hasn't been to church
in 40 years.

987
01:00:50,312 --> 01:00:52,212
40 years.

988
01:00:52,314 --> 01:00:54,043
And he won't talk
to his daughter

989
01:00:54,149 --> 01:00:55,548
because she married someone

990
01:00:55,650 --> 01:00:57,379
who hadn't been
to his church in 20.

991
01:00:58,653 --> 01:01:00,712
How do we undo that?

992
01:01:02,491 --> 01:01:05,289
What about us?

993
01:01:05,394 --> 01:01:07,055
Start over.

994
01:01:08,497 --> 01:01:11,989
Remember what it was that got you
started in the first place?

995
01:01:12,100 --> 01:01:15,069
Build on that.

996
01:01:15,170 --> 01:01:17,070
- Redis cover where--
- Sshhh.

997
01:01:40,529 --> 01:01:43,430
Announcer: It's semi-final time.
Kilnockie nearly promoted

998
01:01:43,532 --> 01:01:45,261
but still in
the Second Division

999
01:01:45,367 --> 01:01:48,097
against Kilmarnock
from the Premier League.

1000
01:01:48,203 --> 01:01:51,468
And no chance of Kilnockie
relinquishing home advantage,

1001
01:01:51,573 --> 01:01:54,201
because we're on neutral ground
at Premier Park,

1002
01:01:54,309 --> 01:01:56,869
where not only are they facing
a Premiership side, Rob,

1003
01:01:56,978 --> 01:01:59,378
they've got to beat them
without Jackie McQuillan.

1004
01:01:59,481 --> 01:02:02,279
After his recent sending off
against Queen of the South,

1005
01:02:02,384 --> 01:02:03,612
he's sitting in the stands.

1006
01:02:03,718 --> 01:02:04,878
- Hey, man.
- Hi, chairman.

1007
01:02:04,986 --> 01:02:07,546
Jackie, Mr. O'Shea
and Mr. Clancy.

1008
01:02:07,656 --> 01:02:10,819
Jackie McQuillan.
Great player this guy.

1009
01:02:10,926 --> 01:02:13,486
Could get used to this gaffer.
Let's make it a habit.

1010
01:02:13,595 --> 01:02:15,222
Aye, aye.

1011
01:02:17,332 --> 01:02:20,062
And that's the experienced
Hugh Dallas as the referee.

1012
01:02:20,168 --> 01:02:21,897
Watch this.
Here we go.

1013
01:02:22,003 --> 01:02:24,403
- Oh, right.
- ( whistle sounds )

1014
01:02:26,508 --> 01:02:28,533
And the semi-final
gets under way.

1015
01:02:28,643 --> 01:02:31,305
The striking on us
for Kilnockie falls

1016
01:02:31,413 --> 01:02:34,712
on Andy Smith
and Owen Coyle.

1017
01:02:34,816 --> 01:02:36,784
The side, of course,
minus McQuillan.

1018
01:02:36,885 --> 01:02:39,911
The supply, it's hoped,
will come from Alan Lawrence.

1019
01:02:40,021 --> 01:02:42,080
And immediately
it's Lawrence in possession.

1020
01:02:42,190 --> 01:02:45,023
A curling cross into the area
but too close to the keeper

1021
01:02:45,127 --> 01:02:46,924
and plucked out of the air
by Meldrum.

1022
01:02:47,028 --> 01:02:49,394
Well, I've been very impressed
with this start, Rob.

1023
01:02:49,498 --> 01:02:52,228
I thought they might defend
in the early stages of this game,

1024
01:02:52,334 --> 01:02:55,497
but they've actually looked to try
to score an early goal, Kilnockie.

1025
01:02:55,604 --> 01:02:57,003
Very ambitious.

1026
01:02:57,105 --> 01:03:00,199
There'll be pressure from Kilmarnock,
of course, the favorites.

1027
01:03:00,308 --> 01:03:02,037
And it's them on the attack

1028
01:03:02,144 --> 01:03:04,874
with that shot directly
at Brian Burns.

1029
01:03:04,980 --> 01:03:07,710
A comfortable save but that
will give him some confidence.

1030
01:03:07,816 --> 01:03:09,215
He's certainly a key man.

1031
01:03:09,317 --> 01:03:11,342
Well, if you don't have
your top goal scorer,

1032
01:03:11,453 --> 01:03:13,216
and you don't have
your best player,

1033
01:03:13,321 --> 01:03:15,721
you might have to rely
on your goalkeeper today.

1034
01:03:15,824 --> 01:03:17,451
That's a confidence
boosting save.

1035
01:03:17,559 --> 01:03:20,392
Here come Kilnockie again.
Again it's Lawrence.

1036
01:03:20,495 --> 01:03:22,395
He's made a good start.
He cuts in.

1037
01:03:22,497 --> 01:03:24,624
This is a real chance
for Kilnockie.

1038
01:03:26,067 --> 01:03:28,558
A brave save by Meldrum
at his feet.

1039
01:03:28,670 --> 01:03:30,570
But he overran it, surely.

1040
01:03:30,672 --> 01:03:33,004
Yes, he definitely did.
It was a brave save.

1041
01:03:33,108 --> 01:03:34,735
But he's a postman,
young Lawrence,

1042
01:03:34,843 --> 01:03:37,403
and he should have delivered
a better finish than he did.

1043
01:03:37,512 --> 01:03:39,912
That was an absolutely
glorious opportunity.

1044
01:03:42,684 --> 01:03:45,084
Here comes
another opportunity.

1045
01:03:45,187 --> 01:03:46,916
It's Owen Coyle.

1046
01:03:47,022 --> 01:03:48,751
Cuts in from
the right hand side

1047
01:03:48,857 --> 01:03:50,381
onto his favorite
left peg.

1048
01:03:50,492 --> 01:03:52,790
The cross aimed
at Andy Smith.

1049
01:03:52,894 --> 01:03:54,691
Smith's header...
and it's a goal !

1050
01:03:54,796 --> 01:03:57,356
A crushing header
from Smith.

1051
01:03:57,465 --> 01:04:00,525
And Kilnockie leads Kilmarnock
by a goal to nil.

1052
01:04:00,635 --> 01:04:03,536
Well, it can't get much better
than this for this side.

1053
01:04:03,638 --> 01:04:05,367
Second Division
against Premier.

1054
01:04:05,473 --> 01:04:08,374
They've really held their own
in the opening half hour.

1055
01:04:08,476 --> 01:04:10,034
And what a sucker punch.

1056
01:04:10,145 --> 01:04:11,703
Beautifully flighted ball,

1057
01:04:11,813 --> 01:04:14,873
and I have to say
a towering, accurate,

1058
01:04:14,983 --> 01:04:18,384
almost unstoppable header
from big Andy Smith.

1059
01:04:19,654 --> 01:04:22,714
We got the goal we weren't sure
we could get, lads, hey?

1060
01:04:22,824 --> 01:04:24,724
Now we have
to make it stand up.

1061
01:04:24,826 --> 01:04:27,386
Don't get caught
ball watching.

1062
01:04:27,495 --> 01:04:29,053
See the ball through
your man.

1063
01:04:29,164 --> 01:04:30,722
That's the way
you shut them down.

1064
01:04:30,832 --> 01:04:32,231
You cut off their movement.

1065
01:04:32,334 --> 01:04:35,565
And remember, you only get
one chance at a Premier team.

1066
01:04:35,670 --> 01:04:38,138
This is our shot at glory,
lads, all right?

1067
01:04:38,240 --> 01:04:40,401
All right,
go and give it to them !

1068
01:04:40,508 --> 01:04:42,032
( together )
Come on, let's go!

1069
01:04:46,181 --> 01:04:49,173
Announcer: Kilmarnock giving it
everything in this second half

1070
01:04:49,284 --> 01:04:52,344
as they try to battle
their way back into the Cup tie.

1071
01:04:52,454 --> 01:04:54,319
They badly want to be
in the final.

1072
01:04:54,422 --> 01:04:55,787
But they are one down, Andy.

1073
01:04:55,890 --> 01:04:58,222
Yes, but they've been camped
in Kilnockie's half

1074
01:04:58,326 --> 01:05:00,521
for the opening half hour
of this second half.

1075
01:05:00,629 --> 01:05:02,426
And their goalkeeper,
Brian Burns,

1076
01:05:02,530 --> 01:05:05,021
has been absolutely
sensational.

1077
01:05:05,133 --> 01:05:07,124
They're looking
a little tired as we get

1078
01:05:07,235 --> 01:05:08,793
to the last quarter
of an hour.

1079
01:05:08,903 --> 01:05:10,598
I am a touch concerned
for them.

1080
01:05:15,110 --> 01:05:17,340
Burns has been a hero so far.

1081
01:05:17,445 --> 01:05:20,437
- Who's got 11 ?
- He's been brave and decisive

1082
01:05:20,548 --> 01:05:23,278
- and he has to continue to be so.
- Who's got 11 ?

1083
01:05:23,385 --> 01:05:25,910
- 11 !
- Curled in toward the near post.

1084
01:05:26,021 --> 01:05:28,922
- 11 !
- Burns has to come for it,

1085
01:05:29,024 --> 01:05:31,720
and he makes a good solid
confident punch.

1086
01:05:31,826 --> 01:05:33,885
Oh, but he's fallen
awkwardly.

1087
01:05:36,164 --> 01:05:38,394
And he's not getting up.
Burns is in trouble.

1088
01:05:38,500 --> 01:05:40,900
This could be
a bad injury blow.

1089
01:05:41,002 --> 01:05:44,733
Almost symbolically, the rain's
come down on Premier Park.

1090
01:05:44,839 --> 01:05:48,400
Black clouds overhead
for the Kilnockie supporters.

1091
01:05:48,510 --> 01:05:50,501
Kelsey, get warmed up.
Come on, quickly.

1092
01:05:50,612 --> 01:05:52,671
Hurry up.
Hey, Kelsey, get warmed up!

1093
01:05:52,781 --> 01:05:54,681
Come on, get warmed up.
Hurry up.

1094
01:05:57,786 --> 01:06:00,346
Announcer: He landed
really awkwardly, Rob.

1095
01:06:00,455 --> 01:06:03,515
As he got into the net,
I think his arm tangled there.

1096
01:06:03,625 --> 01:06:06,685
It went underneath him.
All his weight landed on his shoulder.

1097
01:06:06,795 --> 01:06:08,786
I think he's got
serious problems.

1098
01:06:08,897 --> 01:06:10,922
I think we're about to see
a substitution made.

1099
01:06:19,574 --> 01:06:20,871
Come on, Kelsey,
pay attention.

1100
01:06:20,975 --> 01:06:22,875
- Get your mind on it.
- Kelsey O'Brian

1101
01:06:22,977 --> 01:06:25,878
is the reserve keeper
on the bench. He's 23.

1102
01:06:25,980 --> 01:06:28,710
And he's played soccer
at Dartmouth College

1103
01:06:28,817 --> 01:06:33,049
in the U .S., but he's never
experienced anything like this.

1104
01:06:33,154 --> 01:06:35,213
Well, what a test
for the young man.

1105
01:06:35,323 --> 01:06:37,052
Goodness knows
how he's feeling.

1106
01:06:37,158 --> 01:06:38,785
He knows he's coming on.

1107
01:06:38,893 --> 01:06:40,622
God, what nerves.

1108
01:06:40,729 --> 01:06:42,287
What nerves he must have.

1109
01:06:42,397 --> 01:06:45,389
Here's your chance, son.

1110
01:06:45,500 --> 01:06:47,400
No more small print.

1111
01:06:47,502 --> 01:06:50,596
Just big fucking headlines
up for grabs.

1112
01:06:56,444 --> 01:06:58,844
So, go and grab 'em.

1113
01:07:00,949 --> 01:07:02,678
I was just thinking, Rob,

1114
01:07:02,784 --> 01:07:06,015
we're about to witness probably
the biggest 10 minutes

1115
01:07:06,121 --> 01:07:08,487
in the history
of Kilnockie Football Club.

1116
01:07:08,590 --> 01:07:10,182
And what do they have to do?

1117
01:07:10,291 --> 01:07:13,260
Put a rookie American
with no experience

1118
01:07:13,361 --> 01:07:15,261
and no one's ever heard of,
into the goal.

1119
01:07:15,363 --> 01:07:17,524
The crowd knows he's American.
Listen to them.

1120
01:07:17,632 --> 01:07:19,031
Is that,
''Yank, Yank, Yank,''

1121
01:07:19,134 --> 01:07:22,103
or is it something even
more offensive, I wonder?

1122
01:07:22,203 --> 01:07:23,500
( crowd chanting ''Yank'' )

1123
01:07:26,808 --> 01:07:28,366
But he's got lucky,
I tell ya,

1124
01:07:28,476 --> 01:07:29,807
I thought
that was a corner.

1125
01:07:29,911 --> 01:07:31,742
I thought Burns punched it
straight out.

1126
01:07:31,846 --> 01:07:34,713
The referee has given a goal kick
in all the confusion.

1127
01:07:34,816 --> 01:07:36,716
Gives the goalkeeper
a chance to settle.

1128
01:07:36,818 --> 01:07:38,911
Good clearance up field.
Get settled.

1129
01:07:44,859 --> 01:07:47,726
Dear, oh dear.
Well, that's ominous.

1130
01:07:47,829 --> 01:07:50,992
His first touch of the ball,
a real sclaff.

1131
01:07:51,099 --> 01:07:53,329
He took a chunk of turf.

1132
01:07:53,435 --> 01:07:55,494
And let's hope
his shot stopping

1133
01:07:55,603 --> 01:07:57,332
is better than
his goal kicking.

1134
01:07:58,773 --> 01:08:00,604
Here comes
the Kilmarnock pressure.

1135
01:08:05,947 --> 01:08:07,847
Dealt with quite
comfortably there.

1136
01:08:07,949 --> 01:08:10,850
- Hetherston thumped it clear.
- Fuck, four minutes.

1137
01:08:10,952 --> 01:08:13,512
- Where's he get that from?
- The signal from the touch-line

1138
01:08:13,621 --> 01:08:15,179
is that four minutes
will be added.

1139
01:08:15,290 --> 01:08:17,850
Oh, Christ.
How much time?

1140
01:08:17,959 --> 01:08:19,688
I don't know.
I can't look.

1141
01:08:19,794 --> 01:08:21,853
Agony written
all over the faces

1142
01:08:21,963 --> 01:08:24,693
of the Kilnockie supporters.
Can they hold on?

1143
01:08:24,799 --> 01:08:26,562
How much time
are you giving them?

1144
01:08:26,668 --> 01:08:28,533
Why don't you stick on
a green jersey

1145
01:08:28,636 --> 01:08:31,196
- and make it legal, eh?!
- Calm down, okay?

1146
01:08:31,306 --> 01:08:32,705
You either behave
yourself...

1147
01:08:32,807 --> 01:08:35,207
Who said there's no pressure
in this game?

1148
01:08:35,310 --> 01:08:38,541
Hugh Dallas telling him
in no uncertain terms,

1149
01:08:38,646 --> 01:08:40,273
''Sit down, son.''

1150
01:08:40,381 --> 01:08:42,349
You can blow the whistle
any old time,

1151
01:08:42,450 --> 01:08:44,384
says Gordon McCleod.

1152
01:08:44,486 --> 01:08:47,546
That one last chance possibly

1153
01:08:47,655 --> 01:08:49,282
for Kilmarnock.

1154
01:08:49,390 --> 01:08:51,483
Kilmarnock pressing.
That's a good effort.

1155
01:08:51,593 --> 01:08:54,323
And touched over the top
by Kelsey O'Brian.

1156
01:08:54,429 --> 01:08:56,158
That's a corner kick.

1157
01:08:57,432 --> 01:09:00,162
They're almost there, Rob.
10 seconds to go.

1158
01:09:01,436 --> 01:09:05,372
This could be the last chance
for Kilmarnock.

1159
01:09:07,242 --> 01:09:10,177
And that's a good punch
by O'Brian.

1160
01:09:10,278 --> 01:09:12,007
It's out
of the danger area.

1161
01:09:12,113 --> 01:09:14,445
As the full time
whistle goes.

1162
01:09:14,549 --> 01:09:16,244
It's unbelievable !

1163
01:09:16,351 --> 01:09:19,445
Kilnockie are through
to the final

1164
01:09:19,554 --> 01:09:22,079
of the Scottish Cup
and they'll play,

1165
01:09:22,190 --> 01:09:24,351
believe it or not,
Rangers.

1166
01:09:24,459 --> 01:09:27,189
Well, I can't believe
what I've witnessed this afternoon.

1167
01:09:27,295 --> 01:09:29,160
A Second Division side

1168
01:09:29,264 --> 01:09:32,563
arrived here against
a Premier League side.

1169
01:09:32,667 --> 01:09:35,192
They arrive here
without the top man.

1170
01:09:35,303 --> 01:09:37,203
Without their main striker.

1171
01:09:37,305 --> 01:09:40,706
Their goalkeeper gets carried
off 10 minutes from the end.

1172
01:09:40,808 --> 01:09:42,867
They stick in
a rookie American

1173
01:09:42,977 --> 01:09:45,070
no-one's ever hear of.
Hold out.

1174
01:09:45,179 --> 01:09:47,079
It's unbelievable.

1175
01:09:48,416 --> 01:09:50,384
And victorious scenes
there'll be

1176
01:09:50,485 --> 01:09:52,544
in Kilnockie tonight

1177
01:09:52,654 --> 01:09:55,555
as the reality
of what they've achieved today

1178
01:09:55,657 --> 01:09:57,887
begins to sink in.

1179
01:09:57,992 --> 01:10:00,222
And it will take some
sinking in

1180
01:10:00,328 --> 01:10:02,558
for Kelsey O'Brian.

1181
01:10:02,664 --> 01:10:05,098
He's joined the little team
with the big heart

1182
01:10:05,199 --> 01:10:07,099
and he's come up
with the goods.

1183
01:10:12,807 --> 01:10:14,900
Kelsey.
Here's to your future.

1184
01:10:15,009 --> 01:10:16,738
Well done.

1185
01:10:16,844 --> 01:10:18,402
Well done.

1186
01:10:41,869 --> 01:10:44,269
Gordon: So, Kelsey,
you feeling all right?

1187
01:10:44,372 --> 01:10:47,000
Kelsey: I feel a bit,
you know, sick.

1188
01:10:47,108 --> 01:10:49,599
You know...

1189
01:10:49,711 --> 01:10:51,201
before the semi-final,

1190
01:10:51,312 --> 01:10:54,372
the most people I ever played
in front of was maybe 2,200.

1191
01:10:54,482 --> 01:10:56,712
Uh-huh.
Uh-huh.

1192
01:11:00,321 --> 01:11:04,155
- You ever fish?
- Yeah, with my grandpa as a kid.

1193
01:11:07,161 --> 01:11:09,561
Well, when you're standing
in that river, son,

1194
01:11:09,664 --> 01:11:12,224
there's only one thing
you're concentrating on.

1195
01:11:12,333 --> 01:11:15,894
That wee fly floating
with the current 30, 40 feet away.

1196
01:11:16,004 --> 01:11:18,234
So you mend your line
once or twice,

1197
01:11:18,339 --> 01:11:21,274
but you never take your eye
off the wee fly.

1198
01:11:21,376 --> 01:11:23,708
It's the same thing
with goalkeeping.

1199
01:11:23,811 --> 01:11:25,574
You get the angle you want,

1200
01:11:26,848 --> 01:11:30,113
make sure of your footing,
keep your line,

1201
01:11:30,218 --> 01:11:32,243
then you concentrate
on nothing

1202
01:11:32,353 --> 01:11:34,446
but that wee bouncing ball
out there.

1203
01:11:34,555 --> 01:11:36,250
Everything else goes.

1204
01:11:36,357 --> 01:11:38,086
The fans, the noise,
the colors,

1205
01:11:38,192 --> 01:11:40,092
all the jumping around.

1206
01:11:40,194 --> 01:11:43,254
Now, that's what I want you
to do against the Rangers, eh?

1207
01:11:44,532 --> 01:11:46,124
Go fishing.

1208
01:12:27,875 --> 01:12:29,775
( singing Scottish music )

1209
01:12:49,363 --> 01:12:51,331
( applauding )

1210
01:12:57,438 --> 01:13:01,704
# Oh, the summertime
has come #

1211
01:13:01,809 --> 01:13:06,542
# And the trees
are sweetly blooming #

1212
01:13:06,647 --> 01:13:11,107
# And the wild
mountain thyme #

1213
01:13:11,219 --> 01:13:15,713
# Grows around
the purple heather #

1214
01:13:15,823 --> 01:13:17,723
# Will you go, lassie, go?

1215
01:13:17,825 --> 01:13:20,225
- Are you dancing?
- Are you asking?

1216
01:13:20,328 --> 01:13:21,556
Aye.

1217
01:13:21,662 --> 01:13:26,122
# And we'll all go together #

1218
01:13:26,234 --> 01:13:30,898
# To pull wild mountain thyme #

1219
01:13:31,005 --> 01:13:34,202
# All around
the blooming heather #

1220
01:13:34,308 --> 01:13:37,300
# Will you go, #

1221
01:13:37,411 --> 01:13:40,346
# Lassie, go? #

1222
01:13:45,186 --> 01:13:47,916
- ( music ends )
- Well played, lads.

1223
01:13:57,431 --> 01:13:59,365
Ladies and gentlemen,

1224
01:13:59,467 --> 01:14:01,492
Gordon McCleod.

1225
01:14:01,602 --> 01:14:03,934
( applause )

1226
01:14:24,492 --> 01:14:26,517
It's a great night--

1227
01:14:26,627 --> 01:14:28,527
for this team
and this town.

1228
01:14:30,765 --> 01:14:33,461
But I cannot help wondering
where home is

1229
01:14:33,568 --> 01:14:35,468
if we win the Cup.

1230
01:14:36,470 --> 01:14:39,371
Maybe the owner of the team
could clear this up for us tonight.

1231
01:14:40,741 --> 01:14:43,869
Four months ago you told me
we had to do better.

1232
01:14:45,046 --> 01:14:47,514
We're a First Division
team now.

1233
01:14:47,615 --> 01:14:49,344
Is that good enough?

1234
01:14:50,685 --> 01:14:53,313
Good enough to call
Kilnockie home?

1235
01:14:54,555 --> 01:14:56,546
Well, I'll tell you what,
Gordon,

1236
01:14:56,657 --> 01:14:58,648
I'll make you
the same promise

1237
01:14:58,759 --> 01:15:00,727
I made you
four months ago.

1238
01:15:01,963 --> 01:15:03,931
I promise you the team
stays here...

1239
01:15:04,031 --> 01:15:07,296
( applause )

1240
01:15:10,571 --> 01:15:12,630
if, and this is
what I told him,

1241
01:15:14,609 --> 01:15:16,736
you beat Rangers.

1242
01:15:16,844 --> 01:15:18,573
Oh.

1243
01:15:21,749 --> 01:15:25,048
Eh, now we know
what we're playing for.

1244
01:15:31,158 --> 01:15:33,023
Many of you also know

1245
01:15:33,127 --> 01:15:35,459
that home means
a lot to me.

1246
01:15:36,631 --> 01:15:39,293
I was born in a wee mining town
southwest of Glasgow.

1247
01:15:41,168 --> 01:15:43,500
And miners never forget
where they're from.

1248
01:15:43,604 --> 01:15:45,401
And fishermen remember,
too,

1249
01:15:45,506 --> 01:15:48,771
which is why I've always felt
at home in this town,

1250
01:15:48,876 --> 01:15:51,276
amongst all of you.

1251
01:15:52,380 --> 01:15:55,406
When it's life and death,
you learn quickly who you can trust,

1252
01:15:55,516 --> 01:15:58,314
be it in a mineshaft
or on a fishing boat.

1253
01:15:59,754 --> 01:16:01,654
I approach football
the same way.

1254
01:16:01,756 --> 01:16:04,725
I don't care if you're a good
player or a bad player.

1255
01:16:07,228 --> 01:16:09,890
If you're a good person
I'll work with you.

1256
01:16:11,666 --> 01:16:14,499
But I'd prefer you were a good player
as well as a good person.

1257
01:16:14,602 --> 01:16:17,036
( laughter )

1258
01:16:18,139 --> 01:16:19,936
Now...

1259
01:16:21,042 --> 01:16:23,442
there's a lot of good people
on this team

1260
01:16:23,544 --> 01:16:27,173
and a lot of good people who've been
rooting for them for a lot of years.

1261
01:16:27,281 --> 01:16:30,375
None of our success
could've happened

1262
01:16:30,484 --> 01:16:33,180
without your support.

1263
01:16:33,287 --> 01:16:36,688
Just like none of my success
would have been possible

1264
01:16:36,791 --> 01:16:38,884
without the support of my wife,
Irene.

1265
01:16:38,993 --> 01:16:41,325
- Aye.
- Aye, good on ya.

1266
01:16:41,429 --> 01:16:43,556
( applause )

1267
01:16:50,438 --> 01:16:52,599
There's a lot
of young players

1268
01:16:52,707 --> 01:16:55,733
who think they can be involved
in semis and finals every year.

1269
01:16:57,511 --> 01:16:59,604
But I never played
in a Cup Final

1270
01:16:59,714 --> 01:17:03,115
and I know a lot
of very good players who didn't.

1271
01:17:04,285 --> 01:17:07,482
So cherish this opportunity.

1272
01:17:09,390 --> 01:17:11,290
Now I won't make
any daft promises,

1273
01:17:11,392 --> 01:17:13,485
but we'll go and give
our all on Saturday

1274
01:17:13,594 --> 01:17:15,824
and we'll enjoy it.

1275
01:17:15,930 --> 01:17:17,955
But remember...

1276
01:17:19,300 --> 01:17:22,269
enjoyment to me
is winning.

1277
01:17:22,370 --> 01:17:24,395
All right?
All right?

1278
01:17:24,505 --> 01:17:26,405
Eh? Eh?

1279
01:17:38,686 --> 01:17:40,415
There's one last
official duty

1280
01:17:40,521 --> 01:17:42,512
to perform tonight.

1281
01:17:42,623 --> 01:17:45,990
Not five hours after
our Kilmarnock win

1282
01:17:46,093 --> 01:17:48,926
two of this team's
greatest supporters

1283
01:17:49,030 --> 01:17:51,658
rolled up their sleeves
and went to work.

1284
01:17:51,766 --> 01:17:53,461
( applause )

1285
01:17:53,567 --> 01:17:55,398
The result of their efforts

1286
01:17:55,503 --> 01:17:57,368
should make us all
feel proud.

1287
01:17:58,406 --> 01:18:00,636
( whistles )

1288
01:18:03,310 --> 01:18:05,244
If the coaches and the team

1289
01:18:05,346 --> 01:18:07,473
would please make their way up
to the stage.

1290
01:18:14,221 --> 01:18:16,746
- Go on. Jackie, go on.
- No way.

1291
01:18:16,857 --> 01:18:19,655
There is no way I am putting
one of those jackets on.

1292
01:18:48,322 --> 01:18:51,018
Hi, Jackie, glad to see
you could join us today.

1293
01:18:52,326 --> 01:18:54,419
So this is how
you boys travel?

1294
01:18:54,528 --> 01:18:56,325
( chatter )

1295
01:18:56,430 --> 01:18:58,955
You run out of gas, eh?

1296
01:18:59,066 --> 01:19:01,227
Aye, in a manner of speaking,
gaffer, aye.

1297
01:19:01,335 --> 01:19:03,235
Andy, you made
the squad, son.

1298
01:19:03,337 --> 01:19:05,828
- That's a boost to Rangers.
- As long as we're all here,

1299
01:19:05,940 --> 01:19:08,238
I wanna tell you to keep
your underpants on tonight.

1300
01:19:08,342 --> 01:19:10,207
No sex before the match.

1301
01:19:10,311 --> 01:19:12,677
I don't want you excited

1302
01:19:12,780 --> 01:19:15,647
except on the pitch tomorrow.

1303
01:19:18,853 --> 01:19:22,254
( horns honking )

1304
01:19:26,794 --> 01:19:29,786
David versus Goliath only
scratches the sur--

1305
01:19:29,897 --> 01:19:31,524
Shut up.

1306
01:19:31,632 --> 01:19:33,759
We're joined now,
in the Rangers trophy room,

1307
01:19:33,868 --> 01:19:35,563
by Rangers manager,
Martin Smith.

1308
01:19:35,669 --> 01:19:38,263
Martin, here you are again
in a familiar position--

1309
01:19:38,372 --> 01:19:40,863
the night before another Cup Final
involving the Rangers.

1310
01:19:40,975 --> 01:19:43,808
If you beat Kilnockie tomorrow,
you'll make it a clean sweep.

1311
01:19:43,911 --> 01:19:46,004
The Treble.
No one's done it in 30 years.

1312
01:19:46,113 --> 01:19:49,378
It'd be a lot better if we could keep
Jackie McQuillan out.

1313
01:19:49,483 --> 01:19:51,781
- You bastard.
- Is there anything you'd like to say

1314
01:19:51,886 --> 01:19:53,877
to Gordon tonight?
We did invite him on

1315
01:19:53,988 --> 01:19:56,388
- but he declined.
- Well, you know...

1316
01:19:56,490 --> 01:19:59,891
Gordon's awfully shy.
Hides his light under a bushel.

1317
01:19:59,994 --> 01:20:02,428
Come on back, Gordon.
All is forgiven.

1318
01:20:11,172 --> 01:20:13,265
This is nothing to do
between me and Gordon

1319
01:20:13,374 --> 01:20:17,208
or Jackie and the Rangers.
It's between the two teams.

1320
01:20:17,311 --> 01:20:19,176
Jackie's certainly been
a Rangers killer.

1321
01:20:19,280 --> 01:20:21,043
Have you any plan for him?
( knocking )

1322
01:20:21,148 --> 01:20:23,116
Well, I understand some
of the supporters

1323
01:20:23,217 --> 01:20:25,117
are gonna go over
to his hotel tonight.

1324
01:20:25,219 --> 01:20:27,187
If we can't keep him awake,
we'll have--

1325
01:20:27,288 --> 01:20:29,984
- Gaffer, hey.
- Hey.

1326
01:20:30,090 --> 01:20:31,955
- You doing all right?
- Aye, good. You?

1327
01:20:32,059 --> 01:20:35,256
- Yeah, okay.
- Good.

1328
01:20:35,362 --> 01:20:36,989
Er...

1329
01:20:38,098 --> 01:20:41,397
I-- I don't wanna lose this game
before it starts.

1330
01:20:41,502 --> 01:20:43,299
Stay in your room.
Don't go out.

1331
01:20:43,404 --> 01:20:45,304
Don't drink.

1332
01:20:45,406 --> 01:20:47,306
Don't do what you did
on too many nights.

1333
01:20:47,408 --> 01:20:48,966
- All right?
- Mmm-hmm, mmm-hmm.

1334
01:20:49,076 --> 01:20:50,600
Yup.

1335
01:20:52,546 --> 01:20:54,844
That must give you
the boke, that.

1336
01:20:54,949 --> 01:20:57,679
Seeing that prick sitting there
like that.

1337
01:20:57,785 --> 01:21:00,583
It's water under the bridge.

1338
01:21:00,688 --> 01:21:02,588
Aye, but it could have
been you, gaffer.

1339
01:21:02,690 --> 01:21:05,158
If that bastard had left
his resignation

1340
01:21:05,259 --> 01:21:06,590
in that room in Dundee

1341
01:21:06,694 --> 01:21:08,992
instead of leaving with a raise.

1342
01:21:09,096 --> 01:21:11,462
Aye, that gave me the boke.

1343
01:21:11,565 --> 01:21:13,965
- So he'll be a marked man?
- Closely marked man.

1344
01:21:14,068 --> 01:21:16,400
But it's not just him.

1345
01:21:16,503 --> 01:21:18,300
It's not even
keeping the team in Kilnockie,

1346
01:21:18,405 --> 01:21:20,999
though I want it
with all my heart.

1347
01:21:21,108 --> 01:21:23,235
( laughs )
Come here.

1348
01:21:28,849 --> 01:21:30,976
I was a run-of-the-mill
squad player

1349
01:21:31,085 --> 01:21:33,815
wherever I played.

1350
01:21:33,921 --> 01:21:37,357
Even the Teddy Bears weren't
any good when I made it to Ibrox.

1351
01:21:37,458 --> 01:21:39,392
So I never won anything,

1352
01:21:39,493 --> 01:21:41,358
let alone a championship.

1353
01:21:41,462 --> 01:21:44,056
So tomorrow,
for once in my life,

1354
01:21:44,164 --> 01:21:46,155
I want to win something.
( laughs )

1355
01:21:48,902 --> 01:21:50,631
I want to win the Cup.

1356
01:21:50,738 --> 01:21:52,330
Okay?

1357
01:21:52,439 --> 01:21:55,169
Stay here.

1358
01:21:55,276 --> 01:21:57,176
Stay here, eh?

1359
01:21:57,278 --> 01:21:59,303
- Cheers.
- Okay.

1360
01:22:03,117 --> 01:22:06,280
Oh, what you did
for that Protestant boy

1361
01:22:06,387 --> 01:22:09,254
- was a good thing.
- Protestant boy?

1362
01:22:09,356 --> 01:22:11,916
It had nothing to do
with any church for me, gaffer.

1363
01:22:12,026 --> 01:22:14,551
You know, maybe someday
you'll understand.

1364
01:22:14,662 --> 01:22:17,222
And think the same way
about Kate.

1365
01:22:18,699 --> 01:22:21,327
Hasn't been about that
for a long time.

1366
01:22:22,836 --> 01:22:25,202
Maybe it never was.

1367
01:22:25,306 --> 01:22:26,534
Maybe.

1368
01:22:28,175 --> 01:22:30,040
Eh?

1369
01:22:31,145 --> 01:22:32,737
( screaming )

1370
01:22:32,846 --> 01:22:34,905
It's a nice crowd
you've got here.

1371
01:22:38,218 --> 01:22:40,118
Hi there.
Um, can you give me

1372
01:22:40,220 --> 01:22:43,155
- Jackie McQuillan's room number?
- I'm sorry, ma'am,

1373
01:22:43,257 --> 01:22:46,090
- but I don't know who you--
- I'm Mrs. McQuillan.

1374
01:22:47,194 --> 01:22:50,061
Oh. Of course.

1375
01:22:51,398 --> 01:22:54,561
We're just trying to protect
our players' privacy--

1376
01:22:54,668 --> 01:22:56,693
I can see you're doing
a really nice job

1377
01:22:56,804 --> 01:22:58,704
with the traffic control.

1378
01:22:58,806 --> 01:23:00,706
( knocking )

1379
01:23:06,013 --> 01:23:09,779
Hiya, Jackie.
Remember me?

1380
01:23:09,883 --> 01:23:12,317
- Annie.
- Annie.

1381
01:23:12,419 --> 01:23:14,353
Who could forget?

1382
01:23:15,456 --> 01:23:17,048
Just like old times, eh?

1383
01:23:17,157 --> 01:23:19,921
Being in the Cup Final.

1384
01:23:20,027 --> 01:23:23,224
- Scoring.
- Look, I mean, I'm suppos--

1385
01:23:23,330 --> 01:23:26,493
- I can't go out, you know.
- Who said anything about going out?

1386
01:23:30,471 --> 01:23:32,701
Aren't you wearing
the wrong colors, darling?

1387
01:23:32,806 --> 01:23:35,832
Yeah, well, I never really
thought blue

1388
01:23:35,943 --> 01:23:38,104
was ever a match
for my personality.

1389
01:23:38,212 --> 01:23:40,772
That's her.
I'm telling ya, that's her.

1390
01:23:40,881 --> 01:23:42,781
That's McQuillan's wife.

1391
01:24:01,001 --> 01:24:02,832
( knocking )

1392
01:24:02,936 --> 01:24:05,166
( water running )

1393
01:24:06,840 --> 01:24:08,740
The nutters are on the loose.

1394
01:24:08,842 --> 01:24:10,742
And that's just my team-mates.

1395
01:24:12,146 --> 01:24:14,637
Mum told me that...

1396
01:24:14,748 --> 01:24:16,773
somebody took
the team bus today.

1397
01:24:16,884 --> 01:24:19,614
Well, I'm proud of you.

1398
01:24:19,720 --> 01:24:22,621
So, how do you feel?

1399
01:24:22,723 --> 01:24:25,089
Like I might never
feel this way again.

1400
01:24:27,361 --> 01:24:30,819
I don't know what the hell
I'm gonna do when it's all over.

1401
01:24:37,604 --> 01:24:39,799
I am gonna take care of you

1402
01:24:39,907 --> 01:24:41,636
for the rest of your life.

1403
01:24:41,742 --> 01:24:44,336
You just worry about tomorrow.

1404
01:24:44,445 --> 01:24:47,312
Flooding the bathroom however,

1405
01:24:47,414 --> 01:24:49,541
is not really the best way
to start.

1406
01:24:53,554 --> 01:24:56,182
( draining )

1407
01:24:56,290 --> 01:24:58,349
I should have known.

1408
01:24:58,459 --> 01:25:01,292
You're never gonna get any peace
with this racket going on.

1409
01:25:01,395 --> 01:25:04,489
- Come on.
- What are you doing?

1410
01:25:04,598 --> 01:25:06,566
Just go out.

1411
01:25:06,667 --> 01:25:08,532
I promised Gordon
I'd stay in.

1412
01:25:08,635 --> 01:25:11,001
I'm just talking about a drive
or a cup of coffee.

1413
01:25:11,104 --> 01:25:13,004
Could be the only peace
you'll get.

1414
01:25:13,106 --> 01:25:16,075
I promise I will have you back
before curfew.

1415
01:25:20,781 --> 01:25:23,614
- Ah, there you are.
- Hey! Come on, Jackie.

1416
01:25:25,352 --> 01:25:28,617
- Where are you going?
- Whoa ! Come here !

1417
01:25:28,722 --> 01:25:31,850
Hey!
Hey, Jackie

1418
01:25:31,959 --> 01:25:34,257
have a drink on me.

1419
01:25:34,361 --> 01:25:36,261
- ( glass shatters )
- ( laughing )

1420
01:25:36,363 --> 01:25:40,026
- Are you fucking mental?
- As mental as a Celtic like you !

1421
01:25:40,133 --> 01:25:42,897
People get killed
because of assholes like you !

1422
01:25:43,003 --> 01:25:45,130
- It's a game !
- Jackie, just leave it.

1423
01:25:45,239 --> 01:25:47,173
It's just a fucking game !

1424
01:25:47,274 --> 01:25:50,038
( screaming )

1425
01:25:56,316 --> 01:25:58,284
McQuillan at the gate.

1426
01:26:07,060 --> 01:26:09,688
( siren blares )

1427
01:26:20,107 --> 01:26:22,268
( crowd screams,
bagpipes play )

1428
01:26:26,713 --> 01:26:29,614
Rob: Glasgow woke up this morning
to find Kilnockie striker,

1429
01:26:29,716 --> 01:26:32,082
Jackie McQuillan,
had been released from jail

1430
01:26:32,185 --> 01:26:35,120
following a brawl with Rangers
supporters at a Glasgow hotel.

1431
01:26:35,222 --> 01:26:38,419
Two men were taken
to hospital for treatment.

1432
01:26:38,525 --> 01:26:41,050
Jackie McQuillan was
apparently unhurt.

1433
01:26:45,299 --> 01:26:47,665
Police don't expect
to make a full report

1434
01:26:47,768 --> 01:26:50,703
until sometime
later today or tomorrow

1435
01:26:50,804 --> 01:26:54,205
when it's decided what,
if any charges, will be filed.

1436
01:26:54,308 --> 01:26:56,333
Rob's with me now.
Rob, what's the latest?

1437
01:26:56,443 --> 01:26:58,968
Rob: Andy, I spoke to Nockie
assistant coach, Ian Mc Veigh,

1438
01:26:59,079 --> 01:27:01,479
a few minutes ago.
Jackie is fit to play.

1439
01:27:01,582 --> 01:27:03,880
Whether he does or not
will depend on his manager

1440
01:27:03,984 --> 01:27:05,849
and his father-in-law,
Gordon McCleod.

1441
01:27:05,953 --> 01:27:08,387
And we know all about their
rocky relationship.

1442
01:27:08,488 --> 01:27:11,048
Dad.

1443
01:27:11,158 --> 01:27:13,058
Dad.

1444
01:27:23,570 --> 01:27:25,470
Dad !

1445
01:27:32,913 --> 01:27:35,006
Rob: Realistically,
what are their chances?

1446
01:27:35,115 --> 01:27:37,743
A Second Division team
taking on The Old Firm,

1447
01:27:37,851 --> 01:27:40,012
a team that's never been
to a final

1448
01:27:40,120 --> 01:27:42,714
against a team
that's been 35 times

1449
01:27:42,823 --> 01:27:44,723
and won 27.

1450
01:27:44,825 --> 01:27:48,454
A team with a total payroll
of some quarter of a million pounds

1451
01:27:48,562 --> 01:27:51,087
going up against a team
with seven players alone

1452
01:27:51,198 --> 01:27:53,166
who make more than that.

1453
01:27:53,266 --> 01:27:55,928
A team of Scots
with a rookie American in goal

1454
01:27:56,036 --> 01:27:59,870
taking on a club with players
from nine different countries.

1455
01:27:59,973 --> 01:28:03,340
On paper Kilnockie
haven't a chance.

1456
01:28:05,612 --> 01:28:08,513
I've been reading a lot of
David and Goliath stories

1457
01:28:08,615 --> 01:28:10,640
in the papers this week.

1458
01:28:10,751 --> 01:28:13,219
If I was a reporter,
it'd be my angle too.

1459
01:28:13,320 --> 01:28:16,289
It has a nice ring about it,
except the ring of truth.

1460
01:28:16,390 --> 01:28:18,915
In that match up,
one side had a sword,

1461
01:28:19,026 --> 01:28:21,187
the other a stone.

1462
01:28:21,294 --> 01:28:23,353
In this version,

1463
01:28:23,463 --> 01:28:26,523
we both use
the same weapon.

1464
01:28:26,633 --> 01:28:30,433
This is what we play with,
lads.

1465
01:28:30,537 --> 01:28:33,028
And whoever wants it the more...

1466
01:28:33,140 --> 01:28:34,903
will win.

1467
01:28:35,142 --> 01:28:37,906
We can beat this team.

1468
01:28:38,011 --> 01:28:40,309
I want you to be
street fighters.

1469
01:28:40,414 --> 01:28:42,507
Fight for every loose ball,

1470
01:28:42,616 --> 01:28:44,550
every header.

1471
01:28:44,651 --> 01:28:46,710
When they've got the ball,
be where they are.

1472
01:28:46,820 --> 01:28:49,050
And when we've got it

1473
01:28:49,156 --> 01:28:51,021
I want you to be
where they aren't.

1474
01:28:51,124 --> 01:28:53,024
Personal performance

1475
01:28:53,126 --> 01:28:55,253
and high individual standards
count here.

1476
01:28:56,363 --> 01:28:59,093
So, with that in mind...

1477
01:29:01,435 --> 01:29:04,131
everybody up.
I want a wee fucking bounce here.

1478
01:29:04,237 --> 01:29:05,932
Let's go on the spot.

1479
01:29:06,039 --> 01:29:08,200
Make sure we keep
with the ball early.

1480
01:29:08,308 --> 01:29:10,173
Jump early.
Make them tight.

1481
01:29:10,277 --> 01:29:12,108
And we're in.
And we're out.

1482
01:29:12,212 --> 01:29:14,510
Boylie, Lumber,
keep your eye on the ball.

1483
01:29:14,614 --> 01:29:16,172
Make sure we're setting up
tackles.

1484
01:29:16,283 --> 01:29:18,342
And we're in.
And we're out.

1485
01:29:18,452 --> 01:29:20,352
Don't let them play.
They get the ball,

1486
01:29:20,454 --> 01:29:22,581
we get them tackled.
Don't fucking allow them

1487
01:29:22,689 --> 01:29:25,157
to dictate the game.
You get in there and seize it.

1488
01:29:25,258 --> 01:29:27,089
And we're in.
And we're out.

1489
01:29:27,194 --> 01:29:29,685
Whoa, whoa,
whatever you do,

1490
01:29:29,796 --> 01:29:32,356
don't score early
and piss 'em off.

1491
01:29:32,466 --> 01:29:34,661
Out come the teams,

1492
01:29:34,768 --> 01:29:37,134
and what does it feel like
for these players?

1493
01:29:37,237 --> 01:29:39,501
Andy Gray can certainly
answer that question.

1494
01:29:39,606 --> 01:29:41,506
Andy, you've played
in seven.

1495
01:29:41,608 --> 01:29:43,508
Andy: It's a brilliant time.
Between now

1496
01:29:43,610 --> 01:29:45,703
and the end,
they're not gonna enjoy it.

1497
01:29:45,812 --> 01:29:47,712
None of those players.

1498
01:29:47,814 --> 01:29:50,476
But you get the chance.
You come out, stand and line up.

1499
01:29:50,584 --> 01:29:53,144
It gives you a chance to look
for your family and friends,

1500
01:29:53,253 --> 01:29:55,813
give 'em a little wave.
It's the only time you get

1501
01:29:55,922 --> 01:29:57,787
to relax before
this match starts.

1502
01:30:00,227 --> 01:30:03,025
Rob: And it's a huge day
for the man in the cloth cap.

1503
01:30:03,130 --> 01:30:06,031
Gordon McCleod up against
Martin Smith,

1504
01:30:06,133 --> 01:30:07,896
the opposition manager.

1505
01:30:08,001 --> 01:30:10,026
They haven't spoken
for more than 20 years.

1506
01:30:10,137 --> 01:30:11,968
This is a real grudge match.

1507
01:30:12,072 --> 01:30:14,472
And Kilnockie playing
for their future in Scotland.

1508
01:30:14,574 --> 01:30:16,508
Rob: Playing for their very
future

1509
01:30:16,610 --> 01:30:18,840
without their top striker.

1510
01:30:18,945 --> 01:30:20,845
Rob:
Gordon McCleod felt

1511
01:30:20,947 --> 01:30:22,812
it was a decision
that had to be taken.

1512
01:30:22,916 --> 01:30:25,384
It was a matter of discipline.

1513
01:30:25,485 --> 01:30:28,420
A gamble that will pay off
or a gamble that won't.

1514
01:30:30,423 --> 01:30:32,482
McQuillan on the bench

1515
01:30:32,592 --> 01:30:34,560
as Kilnockie kick-off

1516
01:30:34,661 --> 01:30:36,652
in the Scottish Cup Final.

1517
01:30:38,932 --> 01:30:41,059
And the challenge doesn't come

1518
01:30:41,168 --> 01:30:43,659
much bigger
than tackling Rangers.

1519
01:30:43,770 --> 01:30:45,670
And immediately...

1520
01:30:45,772 --> 01:30:48,036
it's the big favorites
on the attack.

1521
01:30:48,141 --> 01:30:50,666
How come Dad's not playing?

1522
01:30:50,777 --> 01:30:52,938
I don't know, honey.

1523
01:30:53,046 --> 01:30:55,606
And there'll be a lot of defending
to do for Kilnockie.

1524
01:30:55,715 --> 01:30:58,275
Andy: Well, if I was Martin Smith
I'd be saying,

1525
01:30:58,385 --> 01:31:01,479
''Get shots on goal
as early and as many as you can.

1526
01:31:01,588 --> 01:31:03,317
Test this American goalkeeper.

1527
01:31:03,423 --> 01:31:05,323
See what he's really like.''

1528
01:31:05,425 --> 01:31:07,950
For Kilnockie it'll be:
defend as well as you can;

1529
01:31:08,061 --> 01:31:10,529
hopefully get a little
breakaway and a little luck.

1530
01:31:10,630 --> 01:31:13,861
Rob:
What an emotional day this is.

1531
01:31:13,967 --> 01:31:16,936
Kilnockie,
a big-hearted team,

1532
01:31:17,037 --> 01:31:18,937
there's not much doubt
about that,

1533
01:31:19,039 --> 01:31:21,371
but they'll need more
than just big hearts today.

1534
01:31:21,474 --> 01:31:23,066
- Owen, go on.
- They'll need

1535
01:31:23,176 --> 01:31:25,906
to show the sort of ability
they've shown to get here

1536
01:31:26,012 --> 01:31:29,379
if they're going to take this
one step further.

1537
01:31:29,482 --> 01:31:31,677
And it's almost unbelievable.

1538
01:31:43,196 --> 01:31:45,096
Here come Rangers.

1539
01:31:45,198 --> 01:31:48,258
Derek Ferguson is pulling
the strings in the midfield.

1540
01:31:48,368 --> 01:31:50,393
Robertson has the chance.

1541
01:31:50,503 --> 01:31:52,494
It's touched back,
and it's Ferguson's shot.

1542
01:31:52,606 --> 01:31:55,166
And it's fumbled
by Kelsey O'Brian.

1543
01:31:55,275 --> 01:31:57,436
He gathers it
at the second attempt.

1544
01:31:57,544 --> 01:32:00,411
That's the first real
threat to Kilnockie.

1545
01:32:00,513 --> 01:32:02,913
Rob: He did well in the end
but he got lucky.

1546
01:32:03,016 --> 01:32:05,314
- He's bound to be nervous.
- Andy: 25 minutes in.

1547
01:32:05,418 --> 01:32:07,409
He's not had a lot of the ball,
the goalkeeper,

1548
01:32:07,520 --> 01:32:09,647
and I still think
he'll be a touch nervy.

1549
01:32:11,157 --> 01:32:14,058
Rob: That scoreboard
make sencouraging viewing

1550
01:32:14,160 --> 01:32:16,924
for Gordon McCleod
and the Kilnockie supporters.

1551
01:32:17,030 --> 01:32:20,193
Here's yet more pressure

1552
01:32:20,300 --> 01:32:22,200
from Rangers.

1553
01:32:22,302 --> 01:32:23,997
In comes the cross...

1554
01:32:24,104 --> 01:32:26,368
out comes Kelsey O'Brian,
that's a poor punch.

1555
01:32:26,473 --> 01:32:29,101
And it's Ferguson !

1556
01:32:29,209 --> 01:32:31,109
And that's one-nil.

1557
01:32:31,211 --> 01:32:33,042
- Rangers have the lead...
- Jesus !

1558
01:32:33,146 --> 01:32:35,546
- Ah, fuck it!
- after O'Brian's mistake.

1559
01:32:35,649 --> 01:32:38,209
And this time he's
punished by Ferguson.

1560
01:32:38,318 --> 01:32:41,810
- One-nil.
- Andy: He'd done well up till then.

1561
01:32:41,922 --> 01:32:45,153
But you always wondered, could he
keep it going for 90 minutes?

1562
01:32:45,258 --> 01:32:48,489
The answer was,
unfortunately for Kilnockie, no.

1563
01:32:48,595 --> 01:32:50,790
A really poor punch
from the American.

1564
01:32:50,897 --> 01:32:54,458
Ferguson pounces.
It was a mountain to climb.

1565
01:32:54,567 --> 01:32:56,762
It's even bigger than that
now for Kilnockie.

1566
01:33:03,777 --> 01:33:05,938
One-fucking-nothing,
you think that's funny?

1567
01:33:06,046 --> 01:33:08,480
One-nothing against
a bunch of rubbish,

1568
01:33:08,581 --> 01:33:10,481
you're all smiles?

1569
01:33:10,583 --> 01:33:13,017
Marking, horrible.
Finishing, deplorable.

1570
01:33:13,119 --> 01:33:16,020
A bunch of fucking
potato-pickers

1571
01:33:16,122 --> 01:33:18,989
is holding the mighty
Glasgow Rangers to one goal

1572
01:33:19,092 --> 01:33:20,992
and you're happy?!

1573
01:33:21,094 --> 01:33:23,858
Your daughter's wanting to see you.
She's in the boardroom.

1574
01:33:23,964 --> 01:33:26,057
You better go.
She's in the boardroom.

1575
01:33:26,166 --> 01:33:28,066
Okay, lads, settle down.

1576
01:33:28,168 --> 01:33:31,194
One mistake
can make it difficult.

1577
01:33:32,505 --> 01:33:34,405
You don't have
to make it difficult!

1578
01:33:44,284 --> 01:33:46,377
Shut the door, Dad.

1579
01:33:46,486 --> 01:33:48,386
You're good at that.

1580
01:33:55,228 --> 01:33:57,423
Jackie didn't get into a fight
last night

1581
01:33:57,530 --> 01:34:00,431
because he was drunk

1582
01:34:00,533 --> 01:34:02,091
or arrogant

1583
01:34:02,202 --> 01:34:03,794
or just being Jackie.

1584
01:34:03,903 --> 01:34:07,168
He got into a fight
because he was defending me

1585
01:34:07,273 --> 01:34:09,241
and you

1586
01:34:09,342 --> 01:34:11,207
and anyone else
who loves this game

1587
01:34:11,311 --> 01:34:15,077
and believes that it should
heal rifts not cement them.

1588
01:34:15,181 --> 01:34:17,513
Oh no,
you're gonna hear me.

1589
01:34:17,617 --> 01:34:20,586
See, I know that you love
to brood on your betrayals.

1590
01:34:20,687 --> 01:34:22,552
You tie them all up

1591
01:34:22,655 --> 01:34:24,520
into little bundles,
like...

1592
01:34:24,624 --> 01:34:26,057
firewood,

1593
01:34:26,159 --> 01:34:28,753
and then warm
your Gaelic blood

1594
01:34:28,862 --> 01:34:31,660
when you think about them.

1595
01:34:31,765 --> 01:34:33,665
It's not Jackie's fault

1596
01:34:33,767 --> 01:34:36,600
that he was born with talent.

1597
01:34:38,505 --> 01:34:41,406
So stop blaming him
for your own failings.

1598
01:34:41,508 --> 01:34:45,137
It's you
and your jealousy

1599
01:34:45,245 --> 01:34:47,736
and your anger

1600
01:34:47,847 --> 01:34:50,680
that God had the nerve
to give someone else

1601
01:34:50,784 --> 01:34:53,480
so much more
than he gave you.

1602
01:34:54,654 --> 01:34:57,418
I don't suppose there's much
you can do about being stubborn.

1603
01:35:00,560 --> 01:35:02,721
And there's definitely nothing
even you can do

1604
01:35:02,829 --> 01:35:05,593
about getting old.

1605
01:35:05,698 --> 01:35:08,166
But for God's sake,
Dad,

1606
01:35:08,268 --> 01:35:10,793
you don't
have to be stupid.

1607
01:35:17,577 --> 01:35:19,772
I want this game, boys.

1608
01:35:19,879 --> 01:35:22,871
I want the Treble.

1609
01:35:25,885 --> 01:35:27,409
Do you hear me?

1610
01:35:28,788 --> 01:35:32,690
Right?!
Fucking do it!

1611
01:35:32,792 --> 01:35:34,885
Rob: We've just
been asking the question

1612
01:35:34,994 --> 01:35:36,621
during the half time interval

1613
01:35:36,729 --> 01:35:39,129
and it's answered
at the start of the second half.

1614
01:35:39,232 --> 01:35:41,359
McQuillan's on
for the second half.

1615
01:35:41,468 --> 01:35:43,561
- Yes !
- Jackie McQuillan is on.

1616
01:35:43,670 --> 01:35:46,503
He's scored nine goals
in seven Cup Finals, Andy.

1617
01:35:46,606 --> 01:35:48,506
Rob: And four of them
against Rangers.

1618
01:35:48,608 --> 01:35:51,475
He had to come on, it's as
simple as that, Rob.

1619
01:35:51,578 --> 01:35:54,240
One down against
the team chasing Treble.

1620
01:35:54,347 --> 01:35:57,077
McQuillan on the bench?
Not for long.

1621
01:35:57,183 --> 01:35:59,879
He had to come on.

1622
01:36:01,521 --> 01:36:04,012
And I have to say,
what a start he's made

1623
01:36:04,124 --> 01:36:06,058
to the second half.
He looks fit.

1624
01:36:06,159 --> 01:36:07,888
He looks fresh.

1625
01:36:07,994 --> 01:36:10,588
Rob: I think he sent on an angry
young man, Gordon McCleod.

1626
01:36:10,697 --> 01:36:13,495
He's gonna prove to one or two
people that he isn't finished.

1627
01:36:13,600 --> 01:36:16,501
I know he's playing. I can see
he's playing. I've got eyes.

1628
01:36:16,603 --> 01:36:19,834
He's the only player they've got.
I'm coming down.

1629
01:36:19,939 --> 01:36:24,342
The personal feud between McQuillan
and McCleod is no secret.

1630
01:36:24,444 --> 01:36:27,709
But could this be
a managerial masterstroke?

1631
01:36:27,814 --> 01:36:31,215
Andy: He's flying.

1632
01:36:34,787 --> 01:36:37,381
Rob: Rangers in control
and dominating the game.

1633
01:36:37,490 --> 01:36:40,118
Second half.
It's been all Kilnockie.

1634
01:36:40,226 --> 01:36:42,592
Rob: So much so,
at times you'd think

1635
01:36:42,695 --> 01:36:45,391
they're the Premiere side.
It's been an immense performance.

1636
01:36:48,067 --> 01:36:51,161
If it isn't St. Martin come down
to mingle with the less fortunate.

1637
01:36:51,271 --> 01:36:53,296
You've been missing
a good game.

1638
01:36:53,406 --> 01:36:55,670
The little guys are down.
But they're about to rise up

1639
01:36:55,775 --> 01:36:57,367
and bite the big boys
in the ass.

1640
01:36:57,477 --> 01:37:00,139
Gazzer,
pick up McQuillan.

1641
01:37:00,246 --> 01:37:02,214
I don't wanna see his name,
understand?

1642
01:37:02,315 --> 01:37:04,112
Put him in your pocket.

1643
01:37:04,217 --> 01:37:06,208
He's down on the touchline,
is Martin Smith.

1644
01:37:06,319 --> 01:37:08,947
He could stay up in the
director's box no longer.

1645
01:37:10,023 --> 01:37:13,049
Gazzer, wake up!
It's no big secret he's in the game.

1646
01:37:13,159 --> 01:37:15,650
What a good save that was
from Ally Maxwell.

1647
01:37:23,670 --> 01:37:27,606
- ( grunts )
- That's a bad tackle on McQuillan.

1648
01:37:27,707 --> 01:37:29,902
They see him as the big threat

1649
01:37:30,009 --> 01:37:31,772
to their Cup Final chances.

1650
01:37:31,878 --> 01:37:33,937
Crowd:
Off, off, off!

1651
01:37:34,047 --> 01:37:36,311
( screaming )

1652
01:37:36,416 --> 01:37:38,145
A yellow card.

1653
01:37:38,251 --> 01:37:40,014
That's bullshit.

1654
01:37:40,119 --> 01:37:41,882
He should have been booted !

1655
01:37:45,558 --> 01:37:47,458
Performance artist.

1656
01:37:47,560 --> 01:37:49,585
Still taking the low road,
eh, Martin?

1657
01:37:49,696 --> 01:37:52,358
It's a goddamn mugging
and you know it.

1658
01:37:52,465 --> 01:37:54,763
Turning your back again.
You're good at that, eh?

1659
01:37:54,867 --> 01:37:56,596
Always was your best side.

1660
01:37:56,703 --> 01:37:58,796
That's enough. Sit down.
Down. Okay?

1661
01:37:58,905 --> 01:38:01,396
Andy: The message came on
from the touchline,

1662
01:38:01,507 --> 01:38:04,305
''Sort out McQuillan.''
There's absolutely no doubt.

1663
01:38:04,410 --> 01:38:07,004
- And sort them out they have.
- ( whistle )

1664
01:38:07,113 --> 01:38:09,104
Andy: I know I might be
upsetting a few people,

1665
01:38:09,215 --> 01:38:11,206
but I'd love to see them get
an equalizer.

1666
01:38:11,317 --> 01:38:13,251
They're running out of time...

1667
01:38:13,353 --> 01:38:16,516
,

1668
01:38:16,623 --> 01:38:18,113
you're backing Kilnockie?
Never.

1669
01:38:21,894 --> 01:38:23,657
( cheering )

1670
01:38:23,763 --> 01:38:26,129
Hey, Kelsey!

1671
01:38:26,232 --> 01:38:28,166
Supporter: What?
Did they score? What?

1672
01:38:28,268 --> 01:38:30,463
Fucking what?
Tell me.

1673
01:38:30,570 --> 01:38:32,094
Gonna shut up?

1674
01:38:35,375 --> 01:38:38,276
Rob: The agitation is
on the Rangers bench.

1675
01:38:38,378 --> 01:38:40,812
How much time
are we playing here?

1676
01:38:40,913 --> 01:38:42,881
John Rowbotham's had
a look at his watch.

1677
01:38:42,982 --> 01:38:44,882
And it's almost all over.

1678
01:38:44,984 --> 01:38:46,884
Rangers within seconds,

1679
01:38:46,986 --> 01:38:49,750
surely, of holding aloft
the Scottish Cup.

1680
01:38:51,958 --> 01:38:53,858
Jimmy Boyle might have
other ideas.

1681
01:38:53,960 --> 01:38:56,793
His cross !
Up goes McQuillan !

1682
01:38:56,896 --> 01:39:00,195
What a header!
And what a goal !

1683
01:39:00,300 --> 01:39:04,259
- Oh, yes !
- Andy: I don't believe that.

1684
01:39:04,370 --> 01:39:06,998
- Oh my God.
- Rob: That is incredible.

1685
01:39:07,106 --> 01:39:09,574
How do you script things
like this?

1686
01:39:09,676 --> 01:39:11,303
It would have to be him.

1687
01:39:11,411 --> 01:39:13,743
It would have to be
the last minute.

1688
01:39:19,319 --> 01:39:22,550
The color has drained
from the face of Martin Smith.

1689
01:39:22,655 --> 01:39:25,453
Jackie McQuillan
has come back

1690
01:39:25,558 --> 01:39:28,789
to Scottish football
to haunt him.

1691
01:39:28,895 --> 01:39:30,692
Kelsey O'Brian has run

1692
01:39:30,797 --> 01:39:33,425
the full length of the field
to join in the celebrations,

1693
01:39:33,533 --> 01:39:36,229
which will be echoing
around the northeast coastline,

1694
01:39:36,336 --> 01:39:38,600
no doubt about that.

1695
01:39:38,705 --> 01:39:41,037
All those who couldn't travel
to Hampden today...

1696
01:39:41,140 --> 01:39:43,472
will be enjoying this moment.

1697
01:39:44,577 --> 01:39:47,307
- Oh, no.
- No.

1698
01:39:52,885 --> 01:39:54,819
Five million fucking quid

1699
01:39:54,921 --> 01:39:57,014
for a blind man
with two left fucking feet

1700
01:39:57,123 --> 01:39:59,216
who doesn't
even speak English.

1701
01:40:06,933 --> 01:40:09,925
I wanna go first.
I wanna go first.

1702
01:40:10,036 --> 01:40:13,494
- Jackie, the nail in the coffin.
- Aye, gov.

1703
01:40:13,606 --> 01:40:16,404
- Alan, you start us off.
- Done.

1704
01:40:16,509 --> 01:40:18,409
Blackie,
I want you in on this.

1705
01:40:18,511 --> 01:40:19,944
No problem.

1706
01:40:20,046 --> 01:40:21,741
Silky, you go third.

1707
01:40:21,848 --> 01:40:24,078
Any other Bravehearts?

1708
01:40:25,051 --> 01:40:28,418
Rob: This is a cruel way
to settle a football match,

1709
01:40:28,521 --> 01:40:30,386
especially a Cup Final.

1710
01:40:30,490 --> 01:40:32,458
It's all about
winners and losers,

1711
01:40:32,558 --> 01:40:35,789
the joy,
the heartbreak.

1712
01:40:35,895 --> 01:40:39,092
And it's Eddie May
up first for Rangers, Andy.

1713
01:40:41,100 --> 01:40:43,227
Andy: What a day it's been,
Rob.

1714
01:40:43,336 --> 01:40:45,133
One-one after 90 minutes.

1715
01:40:45,238 --> 01:40:47,468
Extra time couldn't
give us a winner,

1716
01:40:47,573 --> 01:40:49,302
so now we're
down to penalties.

1717
01:40:49,409 --> 01:40:51,843
The one thing I'll tell you,
in the next few minutes,

1718
01:40:51,944 --> 01:40:54,572
we'll have a hero
and a villain.

1719
01:40:54,680 --> 01:40:57,706
It's May versus O'Brian.

1720
01:41:00,486 --> 01:41:02,545
And Eddie May scores.

1721
01:41:02,655 --> 01:41:04,452
Strike one to Rangers.

1722
01:41:04,557 --> 01:41:06,855
That gets them off
to the best possible start.

1723
01:41:06,959 --> 01:41:09,120
Andy: Yeah, they obviously
won the toss, Rob,

1724
01:41:09,228 --> 01:41:11,287
because they went in first.
That's important.

1725
01:41:11,397 --> 01:41:13,797
Now Kilnockie are
playing catch-up.

1726
01:41:19,205 --> 01:41:22,663
Rob: Next up is Captain Courageous
for Kilnockie--

1727
01:41:22,775 --> 01:41:24,640
Alan Barnes, the skipper.

1728
01:41:24,744 --> 01:41:26,336
He wanted to take
the first one.

1729
01:41:26,446 --> 01:41:28,846
He wanted to take
the responsibility.

1730
01:41:28,948 --> 01:41:31,007
Barnes versus Maxwell.

1731
01:41:32,919 --> 01:41:36,411
And he sends him
the wrong way.

1732
01:41:36,522 --> 01:41:39,923
Kilnockie are one-one
in the penalty shoot out.

1733
01:41:44,464 --> 01:41:46,022
They'll feel
a bit better now,

1734
01:41:46,132 --> 01:41:47,997
with that one going in.

1735
01:41:49,302 --> 01:41:52,294
The pressure unloaded
for Barnes.

1736
01:41:52,405 --> 01:41:53,770
And the pressure now on,

1737
01:41:53,873 --> 01:41:55,738
for young Robertson.

1738
01:41:59,645 --> 01:42:01,670
He blasted it,
Robertson.

1739
01:42:01,781 --> 01:42:04,841
And scored.
Two-one in the shoot out.

1740
01:42:04,951 --> 01:42:06,782
That's your type
of penalty, isn't it?

1741
01:42:06,886 --> 01:42:09,081
Low on finesse,
high on velocity.

1742
01:42:09,188 --> 01:42:11,179
Andy: My type of penalty
finds the net.

1743
01:42:11,290 --> 01:42:12,188
( laughs )

1744
01:42:14,994 --> 01:42:17,724
This man knows
all about penalties--

1745
01:42:17,830 --> 01:42:19,229
Kenny Black.

1746
01:42:21,100 --> 01:42:23,568
You don't get much better
than that.

1747
01:42:23,669 --> 01:42:26,638
Left foot ferocious.
Top corner.

1748
01:42:26,739 --> 01:42:28,604
Andy: A little bit
of emotion as well.

1749
01:42:28,708 --> 01:42:30,608
( laughing )
But all wrapped up.

1750
01:42:30,710 --> 01:42:32,735
A little apology.

1751
01:42:37,917 --> 01:42:39,316
Now it's--

1752
01:42:39,418 --> 01:42:41,249
John Stone !

1753
01:42:41,354 --> 01:42:43,379
And that's three-two
to Rangers.

1754
01:42:43,489 --> 01:42:45,719
O'Brian went left,
the ball went the other way.

1755
01:42:45,825 --> 01:42:49,317
And Rangers again
have the edge.

1756
01:42:49,428 --> 01:42:52,022
Andy: Five pretty good penalties
I have to say.

1757
01:42:53,132 --> 01:42:56,568
That's cool.
A little wink to Ally Maxwell.

1758
01:42:56,669 --> 01:42:59,001
- He fancies this, doesn't he?
- They call him Silky.

1759
01:43:01,941 --> 01:43:04,205
He just passed
that into the net,

1760
01:43:04,310 --> 01:43:05,709
picked his spot.

1761
01:43:05,811 --> 01:43:08,006
Again,
Maxwell chose wrong.

1762
01:43:08,114 --> 01:43:10,139
And it's three each.

1763
01:43:10,249 --> 01:43:12,649
Andy: At the moment neither
goalkeeper's getting

1764
01:43:12,752 --> 01:43:14,652
anywhere near a penalty.

1765
01:43:14,754 --> 01:43:17,154
Now Harris for Rangers.

1766
01:43:17,256 --> 01:43:19,747
It's gone through.

1767
01:43:19,859 --> 01:43:22,453
O'Brian gave it his best shot
but he couldn't keep it out.

1768
01:43:24,363 --> 01:43:26,092
Rangers piling on
the pressure.

1769
01:43:27,967 --> 01:43:30,128
Sandy Stewart.

1770
01:43:32,471 --> 01:43:35,463
- ( grunts )
- A save by Maxwell !

1771
01:43:35,575 --> 01:43:37,770
The first save
of the shoot out

1772
01:43:37,877 --> 01:43:41,506
denies the former
Airdrie player.

1773
01:43:41,614 --> 01:43:43,309
He can't believe it.

1774
01:43:43,416 --> 01:43:46,317
What's going on?
Is it bad?

1775
01:43:46,419 --> 01:43:49,877
We're dead,
unless Kelsey makes this save.

1776
01:43:54,560 --> 01:43:56,858
Gordon: When you're standing
in that river, son,

1777
01:43:56,963 --> 01:43:59,397
there's only one thing
you're concentrating on,

1778
01:43:59,498 --> 01:44:02,467
the wee fly floating
with the current.

1779
01:44:02,568 --> 01:44:05,469
It's the same thing
between the sticks, Kelsey.

1780
01:44:05,571 --> 01:44:07,562
You get the angle you want,

1781
01:44:07,673 --> 01:44:10,164
you concentrate on nothing
but that wee ball out there.

1782
01:44:10,276 --> 01:44:12,039
Everything else goes,

1783
01:44:12,144 --> 01:44:15,443
the fans, the noise,
the colors.

1784
01:44:15,548 --> 01:44:18,108
That's what
I want you to do.

1785
01:44:18,217 --> 01:44:19,809
Go fishing.

1786
01:44:25,091 --> 01:44:27,457
- ( groans )
- What a fine save !

1787
01:44:27,560 --> 01:44:29,528
The fairy tale continues !

1788
01:44:30,696 --> 01:44:32,391
Yes ! Yes !

1789
01:44:32,498 --> 01:44:34,261
Yes !

1790
01:44:34,367 --> 01:44:37,097
Yeah !

1791
01:44:38,204 --> 01:44:41,537
The emotional roller-coaster
rolls on.

1792
01:44:41,641 --> 01:44:44,769
And cometh the hour.
Cometh the man.

1793
01:44:44,877 --> 01:44:47,004
Who would Kilnockie want
at this stage...

1794
01:44:47,113 --> 01:44:49,513
to step up,
to strike the penalty

1795
01:44:49,615 --> 01:44:51,879
which can keep them
in the Cup Final?

1796
01:44:51,984 --> 01:44:54,009
You would have to answer it
with two words:

1797
01:44:54,120 --> 01:44:56,054
Jackie McQuillan.

1798
01:44:56,155 --> 01:44:58,419
Andy: In normal circumstances, Rob,
I would agree,

1799
01:44:58,524 --> 01:45:00,924
but let me
tell you something,

1800
01:45:01,027 --> 01:45:03,086
these are not
normal circumstances.

1801
01:45:03,195 --> 01:45:07,461
This is pressure
the likes of even Jackie McQuillan

1802
01:45:07,566 --> 01:45:09,033
- hasn't faced before.
- ( crowd taunting )

1803
01:45:11,470 --> 01:45:14,371
McQuillan, you fucking drunk,
you couldn't kick your own ass !

1804
01:45:14,473 --> 01:45:18,409
Can he keep Kilnockie
in the match?

1805
01:45:45,037 --> 01:45:48,871
Rob: Oh, what a save
by Ally Maxwell !

1806
01:45:48,974 --> 01:45:51,169
Rangers have won the Cup!

1807
01:45:51,277 --> 01:45:54,110
It's heartbreak for McQuillan.

1808
01:45:54,213 --> 01:45:56,238
It's heartbreak for Kilnockie.

1809
01:45:56,348 --> 01:45:59,875
The fairy tale is over.

1810
01:47:21,267 --> 01:47:24,100
If you're gonna be a McCleod,
son,

1811
01:47:24,203 --> 01:47:26,694
you're gonna have to learn
to stand on your own two feet.

1812
01:47:26,806 --> 01:47:28,501
Sorry, gaffer.

1813
01:47:28,607 --> 01:47:31,303
That's football, son.

1814
01:47:37,683 --> 01:47:41,744
McCleod and McQuillan walk off
side-by-side...

1815
01:47:41,854 --> 01:47:43,981
leaving the Hampden stage.

1816
01:47:44,089 --> 01:47:47,024
And could this be
the curtain-call for Kilnockie?

1817
01:47:47,126 --> 01:47:49,924
The road to glory
has ended here.

1818
01:47:50,029 --> 01:47:51,894
And if they move to Ireland,

1819
01:47:51,997 --> 01:47:55,023
they've left their supporters
with a performance to remember.

1820
01:47:55,134 --> 01:47:57,568
Kilnockie may have
lost today,

1821
01:47:57,670 --> 01:47:59,570
but they did not fail.

1822
01:48:04,677 --> 01:48:06,577
How does it feel to have
come so close?

1823
01:48:06,679 --> 01:48:09,113
What can I say, lads?
What can I say?

1824
01:48:09,215 --> 01:48:11,547
Just, you know--

1825
01:48:11,650 --> 01:48:13,880
cheers.
Cheers, all right?

1826
01:48:13,986 --> 01:48:16,181
Better luck in Dublin.

1827
01:48:19,692 --> 01:48:21,956
I don't think so,
fellas.

1828
01:48:22,061 --> 01:48:24,222
Look at these people.

1829
01:48:24,330 --> 01:48:26,230
You can't buy
this kind of loyalty.

1830
01:48:26,332 --> 01:48:28,562
I think we're gonna stay
right here.

1831
01:48:28,667 --> 01:48:30,692
Next year we're gonna
win this thing.

1832
01:48:43,382 --> 01:48:46,283
I can't do anything
about getting old...

1833
01:48:48,454 --> 01:48:50,649
my-- my wee lamb.

1834
01:48:54,193 --> 01:48:56,889
- It's all right.
- I missed you.

1835
01:48:56,996 --> 01:48:58,896
It's a good feeling.

1836
01:48:58,998 --> 01:49:01,796
A good feeling.
A feeling of relief.

1837
01:49:01,901 --> 01:49:04,768
Brian, hold this.

1838
01:49:04,870 --> 01:49:05,996
Gordon.

1839
01:49:08,474 --> 01:49:10,999
Winning by penalty kicks
isn't winning.

1840
01:49:11,110 --> 01:49:13,408
Maybe not...

1841
01:49:13,512 --> 01:49:17,812
but, I'd rather see my name
on the Cup than yours.

1842
01:49:20,619 --> 01:49:22,587
Cheers.

1843
01:49:26,558 --> 01:49:29,391
Here.
You hold it, yeah?

1844
01:49:29,495 --> 01:49:31,554
Left hand.

1845
01:49:31,664 --> 01:49:34,132
Pound says wee Jackie
gets the first fish.

1846
01:49:34,233 --> 01:49:37,725
If he catches one before me,
he's walking home.

1847
01:49:42,274 --> 01:49:44,003
( reel spinning )

1848
01:49:44,109 --> 01:49:46,134
Kate:
Fish in !

1849
01:49:47,246 --> 01:49:50,306
- Eh?
- Fish in !

1850
01:49:50,416 --> 01:49:52,145
Go on, Katie !

1851
01:49:58,090 --> 01:50:00,058
Whew!

1852
01:50:03,929 --> 01:50:06,295
At least we're not
walking home, eh?

